Overview

Here I present a preliminary exploration of data from pinto abalone that were tagged and tracked at Pt. Loma between 2015-11-13 and 2016-05-17. The goal is to evaluate how to best filter the results to minimize positional errors and maximize information about movement distances, aggregation, etc.

For starters, filtered data consisted of a subset of abalone and sync tag data that had a horizontal position error (HPE) of \(\leq\) 50, a speed between detections of \(\leq\) 0.2 m/s, a computed distance between detections of \(\leq\) 20 m. This reduced the number of detections from 23116 to 21788 for abalone tags (5.7% of detections removed), and 146603 to 133071 for sync tags (9.2% of detections removed).

Summary plots

Abalone tag data

Abalone tag detections over time

Histograms of abalone tag detections by weekly (7-d) bins, from the earliest to the latest detection of any tag.

Abalone tag movement distances between detections

Most abalone movements were less than 20 m between detections.

Abalone tag movement speed between detections

The vast majority of abalone speeds appears to be less than 0.2 m/s, which could serve as a first pass cut-off for filtering.

Abalone tag movement distances between detections - FILTERED

Histograms of abalone tag movement distances after data were filtered by HPE (50), distance (20 m), and speed (0.2 m/s) (.

Sync tag data

Sync tag detections over time

Was sync tag A69-9002-16318 only deployed during Week 15-ish? There is a large data gap in the first third of the time series. The increasing pattern of detections, with regular spikes, is a bit suspicious. I’ll have to look into that.

Sync tag movement distances between detections

Interestingly, sync tag momements are often quite large.

Convex hulls around pinto abalone detections - ALL

Convex hulls that encapsulate each tagged abalone are shown in one plot. For clarity, only data from abalone tags with a minimum of 100 detections are shown. Apparently few, if any, abalone were observed in the SE portion of the study site.
